    <title>Combined summary - SPV bitcoind? (was: Introducing BitcoinKit.framework)</title>
    <updated>2023-06-07T14:02:13.023308+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2013-July/002917.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>Discussions within the Bitcoin community have been focused on proposals related to scalability and security. One proposal made by Peter Todd suggests implementing partial UTXO sets, which would allow nodes to gradually become full nodes over time, improving security, privacy and scalability of the network. However, concerns have been raised about the potential dangers of using Simplified Payment Verification (SPV) mode in Bitcoin, as it transfers all control on validation rules to miners, potentially leading to a majority coalition of miners changing block reward rules.There have also been discussions on developing SPV bitcoinds that reduce disk storage usage while maintaining full functionality, and desktop clients that download blocks as they are created, building up a more complete UTXO set over time. However, there are concerns about serious privacy issues with SPV nodes, as their peers know that any transaction sent to them is guaranteed to be from the node rather than relayed, and bloom filters may not be helpful with payment protocols that don't exist yet.Anti-DoS measures have also been discussed, with suggestions such as prioritizing existing users over new ones, and old coins over new coins. The libcoin/bitcoind client has been suggested as a potential solution to the scalability issue, downloading the entire blockchain 3.5 times faster than the bitcoin/bitcoind client.The email exchanges and forum threads also touch on issues with compiling libcoin on Mac OSX and funding for development work. Overall, these discussions provide insights into ongoing developments and challenges in the Bitcoin community.</summary>
